# Fix: Approval button should send a bus reply message

Your orchestrator is cec50b17:0. Work inside `.synapse/worktrees/developer-26-approval-button-fix`. Commit your changes. Do not push.

## The bug

When the human clicks "✓ approve" on a `needs_approval` message in S-Deck, the frontend calls `POST /api/messages/:id/approve` which calls `approveMessage(id)` in `src/db.ts` — this only sets `approved_at` timestamp. It does **not** send a new bus message back to the agent. The agent is waiting on `read_messages` for a reply confirming approval, but never gets one.

## Fix

In `src/dashboard.ts`, update the `POST /api/messages/:id/approve` handler to also send a reply message from `"human"` to the original message's `from_id`:

```typescript
app.post('/api/messages/:id/approve', (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const id = parseInt(String(req.params.id), 10);
  if (isNaN(id)) { res.status(400).json({ error: 'invalid id' }); return; }

  // Get the original message to know who to reply to
  const msg = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM messages WHERE id = ?').get(id) as any;
  approveMessage(id);

  // Send a reply from "human" to the requesting agent so read_messages delivers it
  if (msg) {
    sendMessage('human', msg.from_id, 'Approved.', 5, false, undefined, msg.task_id ?? null);
  }

  res.json({ ok: true });
});
```

You'll need to import `sendMessage` (already exported from `src/db.ts`) if it's not already imported in `src/dashboard.ts`. Check the existing imports at the top — it may already be there.

Also check `POST /api/messages/:id/select-option` — same pattern: when a human selects an option, a reply should be sent with the selected option text so the agent knows which option was chosen:

```typescript
app.post('/api/messages/:id/select-option', (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const id = parseInt(String(req.params.id), 10);
  if (isNaN(id)) { res.status(400).json({ error: 'invalid id' }); return; }
  const { option_index } = req.body as { option_index: number };

  const msg = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM messages WHERE id = ?').get(id) as any;
  selectOption(id, option_index);

  // Notify the agent of the selected option
  if (msg) {
    const options = msg.request_options ? JSON.parse(msg.request_options) : [];
    const chosen = options[option_index] ?? `option ${option_index}`;
    sendMessage('human', msg.from_id, chosen, 5, false, undefined, msg.task_id ?? null);
  }

  res.json({ ok: true });
});
```

Check `src/db.ts` for the `db` instance — it's a module-level variable. In `src/dashboard.ts` you may need to import it directly or use `getDb()` if such a function exists. Check existing DB usage in dashboard.ts to see the pattern.

Build with `npm run build` and verify clean.

